Turkey Is Expanding Diplomatic Horizons
Long before Turkey tried to enter the European Union, the European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 steps in Asia, lies one of the most beautiful relics of this failed imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in neo-Renaissance style.
This is at least what the tour guides tell you.
The building stands between the end of the platforms with a tower on each of its corners looking at the world as some German provincial municipalities.
The stone is dirty.
The entire building is slightly decadent.
But once inside the ticket office from the folding ceiling, there is no doubt about the size of the enterprise than what was the most western passage.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a retardant to the imperial game, wanted to realize its ambitions to dominate the Middle East through this railway that ran in Damascus, Baghdad and beyond in what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany’s imperial ambitions sank during the First World War.
His railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
The relative isolation from the surrounding region, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has passed.
British and dominant forces advanced out of Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was bad news for Hyderpasha station, too.
In 1917, a munitions train exploded, destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was a sabotage.
Since then it has slowly gone into disarray, largely surpassed by history.
But today, this railway outlet for Anatolia and all the points to the east, serves - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's ever-larger diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party (AKP) has created a whole new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from its surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has passed.
Now there is a new policy of commitment.
Notably, the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To estimate the parameters of this new foreign policy, I boarded the sleeping carriage for the Turkish capital Ankara, to visit one of the main foreign policy experts of the AKP, the Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning — about ten and a half hours later — after a run-off along the tracks that produced the old-world cadence of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital — proposed as a new city for a secular state intent on turning its back on its Ottoman past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamic roots represents an exemplary shift in the Turkish consensus.
He suggested some suspicions in the West, most notably in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern structure of stone and steel - built ad hoc - in a developing suburb, surrounded by built-up media malls and power patisseries, where managers in business suits - both men and women - meet first to make a contract.
Suat Kinikiloglu could be a centre-right politician from almost any other political party in Europe.
Complete, tie, I'm sure he also had a Blackberry.
“The goal of the foreign-policy party is now to reintegrate Turkey with its closest neighbors.
The Cold War was an anomaly,” he says.
Turkey has been cut off from its hinterland.
Today it must look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't the case either.
They must be both.
"But certainly at some point," I ask, "will Turkey be forced to decide?"
"Turkey," he says, "doesn't want to face that choice."
Then he points out a point that almost all of those I have spoken with here have recited in memory: its links not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus, and all around the Black Sea, are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, the whole of Europe can metaphorically traverse those railway lines to the east through Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha Station, after another blank night, I think of those two German gentlemen Herr Ritter and Herr Conu who had looked at this building built 100 years ago.
How surprised it would be to find that Europe's Middle Eastern ambitions can now be largely in the hands of Turkey.
And while I wait at the ferry terminal that takes me back through the Bosphorus, I remember that in those days Turkey has always been called "the sick man of Europe".
Then at least there seemed to be no doubt about which continent to make claims about this fascinating country.
