The "bee car" to avoid collisions
As part of the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, and especially by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, taking, for example, the flight of bees, knows how to avoid accidents.
It is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
The engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Center developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and the Development of Brand Management, the BR23C is an expansion of Nissan’s four-area Safety Shield.
This robot is intended to improve the ability to prevent collisions in the vehicles of the manufacturer.
During flight, each bee creates its own personal oval-shaped space that is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important thing is the compound eyes of bees, able to see in all directions at an angle above 300 degrees, and that allow the insect to fly uninterruptedly into its personal space.
To recreate this visual feature, the engineers developed what they called a localization laser (Laser Range Finder).
This mechanism detects obstacles facing the BR23C for a radius within two meters and with a maximum width of 180 degrees, calculates the distance from the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor that immediately, allows to prevent collision.
“As soon as it detects an obstacle, the small robot mimics a bee’s movements and immediately changes direction by rotating the wheels at a right or higher angle to avoid a collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the evasion maneuver is totally instinctive.
“If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deflect up or down, and not even diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction in which its wheels can rotate and not taking advantage of infinite directions and ways as bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid collisions.
“This device only needs to process the information every few seconds, and to act from this data.
It does not require information storage or intuitive manoeuvre logic, so it can work without interruptions and with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we’re not talking about gigabytes of memory, and not even mega.”
It is the first step towards the development of new technologies for the immediate prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan hopes will be standard in cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than lithium-ion batteries.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of the units with a GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to the destination avoiding the obstacles present in the route.
