The fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurers, based on data from people’s medical purchases, often refuse to enter into an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
“There is a privacy program according to which the use of prescription drug data depends in any case on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it’s like entrusting the chicken to the fox,” the Washington Post writes citing Richard Dick, the program’s author, to follow drug prescriptions.
Insurance companies subordinate the insurance rate and the amount due in the event of a claim to the health status of the potential customer and if they consider the risk too high they do not cover the insurance.
A long time ago the client had to undergo a medical visit and the contract was concluded only after the outcome of the examination.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure 10 years ago: based on the customer’s identification code, you can easily get information from pharmacies about which medicines he has bought in the last year and a half and from this the program shows what diseases he suffers and what health conditions he is in.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers this means that the level of fat in the blood is practically incurably high and is classified as the highest risk category.
There are various versions of the program on the market, some also determine the risk multiplier, so the insurer in addition to paperwork does not remain much, even if there are small difficulties.
Among the downsides is that some drugs are usable for several purposes, e.g. some compounds are usable against migraines or heat bubbles, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from the point of view of insurance - commercial, is valid as a factor of increased risk, the first two do not.
For the request and data processing companies have been formed separately and these, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the patient’s approval.
Now the authorities are forcing them to do so even if they have not so far imposed fines for negligence.
Some firms have also recently processed the results of laboratory tests and linked them to drug consumption data in order to provide a more accurate picture of patients’ health status.
More and more companies have access to data and, at the same time, control of usage will be increasingly difficult.
There is a separate privacy law, but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
In front of the Congress there is a bill that gives the authorities control powers to companies specialized in data service.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: for this reason he has developed a program that links the forwarding data with the approval expressed by the person concerned.
Another issue is that the person concerned cannot so much deny approval because otherwise insurers do not conclude the contract.
So in the end the chickens are entrusted to the clemency of the fox.
